'''Kamitsukeno no Tamichi''' (田道, birth date unknown - 55th year of {{ill|Emperor Nintoku|ja|仁徳天皇|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emperor Nintoku|qq=}}’s reign) was a warrior of the Nintoku court. His clan and title are not described in the ''{{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nihon Shoki|qq=}}'', but the ''{{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|ja|新撰姓氏録|1=Shinsen Shōjiroku|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinsen Shōjiroku|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinsen Shōjiroku|qq=}}'' refers to him as '''Tamichi no Kimi''' (田道公) with the kabane title of ''Kimi''.
== Overview ==
In the 53rd year of Emperor Nintoku's reign, {{ill|Silla|ja|新羅|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Silla|qq=}} neglected its tribute obligations. Tamichi’s elder brother, {{ill|Takehase|ja|竹葉瀬|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takehase|qq=}}, was dispatched as an envoy to investigate. Later, Tamichi led a military force to defeat the Silla troops. During the campaign, he captured and brought back the inhabitants of four settlements.
In the 55th year of Nintoku's reign, Tamichi was sent to suppress a rebellion by the {{ill|Emishi|ja|蝦夷|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Emishi|qq=}}, but he was defeated and killed at the Ishinomito waterway. After his death, his attendant gave Tamichi’s keepsake, a jade he had wrapped around his hand, to his wife, who, stricken with grief, took her own life. Later, when the Emishi desecrated Tamichi’s grave, a giant serpent emerged and attacked them, causing many fatalities.<ref>{{Cite book|lang=ja|author=Kudō Masaki|title=The Ancient History of the Emishi|publisher={{ill|Yoshikawa Kōbunkan|ja|吉川弘文館|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshikawa Kōbunkan|qq=}}|year=2019|page=71}}</ref>
== Deification ==
Tamichi, who was sent north to suppress the Emishi, was later venerated as a deity of frontier development in {{ill|Hokkaido|ja|北海道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hokkaido|qq=}} and {{ill|Tohoku region|ja|東北|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tohoku region|qq=}}.<ref>https://toyohirajinja.or.jp/</ref> Major shrines dedicated to him include: * {{ill|Saruka Shrine|lt=Saruka Shrine|lt=Saruga Shrine|ja|猿賀神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saruga Shrine|qq=}} * {{ill|Toyohira Shrine|ja|豊平神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyohira Shrine|qq=}} * {{ill|Shinano Shrine|ja|信濃神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinano Shrine|qq=}}
== Banknote Depiction == [[File:Early one yen banknote front and reverse.jpg|thumb|Front and reverse of an early one-yen banknote issued by the {{ill|Second National Bank of Japan|ja|第二国立銀行|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Second National Bank of Japan|qq=}}. The right of the front features Tamichi.]] {{main|National Bank Notes of Japan#One Yen Note}} In 1873 ({{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji|13=User:Immanuelle/Meiji era|qq=}} 6), Tamichi was depicted on the one-yen convertible banknotes issued by the National Bank.<ref name="uemura">Uemura Takashi, ''Portraits on Banknotes in Modern History,'' Yoshikawa Kōbunkan, 2015, pp. 66–67. ISBN 978-4-64-203845-4</ref>
Two theories exist regarding the design of the note: one suggests it depicts Kamitsukeno no Tamichi fending off a surprise attack by the Emishi, while the other posits it as depicting {{ill|Minamoto no Tametomo|ja|源為朝|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Tametomo|qq=}} defending against Kudo Shigemitsu’s fleet. Notably, the figure is depicted with a disproportionately large head relative to the body, an unusual stylistic choice.<ref name="uemura"/>
== Legend == Legends about Tamichi are preserved at the {{ill|Saruka Shrine|lt=Saruka Shrine|lt=Saruga Shrine|ja|猿賀神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Saruga Shrine|qq=}} in {{ill|Hirakawa, Aomori|ja|平川市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hirakawa, Aomori|qq=}}, {{ill|Aomori Prefecture|ja|青森県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Aomori Prefecture|qq=}}, and the {{ill|Toriya Shrine|ja|鳥屋神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toriya Shrine|qq=}} in {{ill|Ishinomaki|ja|石巻市|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ishinomaki|qq=}}, {{ill|Miyagi Prefecture|10=ja|11=宮城県|ja|宮城県|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Miyagi Prefecture|qq=}}.<ref>http://saruka.webcrow.jp/</ref><ref>https://www.miyagi-jinjacho.or.jp/jinja-search/detail.php?code=310010081</ref>
== Genealogy == According to the ''Nihon Shoki,'' Tamichi was the son of {{ill|Aratawake|ja|大荒田別命|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōaratabe no Mikoto|qq=}} and the younger brother of {{ill|Takehase|ja|竹葉瀬|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Takehase|qq=}}.
== References == * ''Nihon Shoki,'' Volume 11, Emperor Nintoku’s 55th Year.
